                <!-- Article 1 -->
                <mj-text mj-class="body-title">
                    <a
                            href="https://www.boj.or.jp/en/statistics/money/ms/ms2307.pdf"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noreferrer"
                            style="text-decoration: none; color: black;"
                    >
                        Bank of Japan Releases Preliminary Money Stock Figures for July 2023, Providing Comprehensive
                        Analysis on a Wide Range of Component
                    </a>
                </mj-text>

                <mj-text mj-class="location">
                    Asia - Japan
                </mj-text>

                <mj-text mj-class="location">
                    Bank of Japan
                </mj-text>

                <mj-text mj-class="date">
                    Wednesday, August 09, 2023
                </mj-text>

                <mj-text mj-class="body-text">
                    The Research and Statistics Department of the Bank of Japan released preliminary figures for the
                    money stock in July 2023. The M1, M2 and M3 figures along with Currency in circulation, Deposit
                    Money, Quasi-money and Certificates of deposit (CDs) were displayed and showed varying rates of
                    changes from the previous year. Also, the report shows figures for broadly-defined liquidity (L)
                    which includes M3 and other components.

                    The statistical data also covered the components of L such as Pecuniary trusts, Investment trusts,
                    Bank debentures, Straight bonds, Commercial paper issued by financial institutions, Government
                    securities and Foreign bonds, each with their yearly percentage changes.

                    The report includes average amounts outstanding for each category, presenting them in trillions of
                    yen.

                    The statistics were noted to include revised figures and seasonally adjusted percent changes. In
                    further detail, the report excludes pension trusts and investment trusts, subordinated bonds but
                    includes dematerialized commercial paper, treasury discount bills and FILP bonds.
                </mj-text>

